# CLAUDE.md — templestay for Claude Code

<!-- templestay-generated-from: shared/templestay/instructions/CLAUDE.md.in -->

Use the native `templestay` Claude Code preset. This is a Claude-native surface,
not a Copilot instruction migration and not an `AGENTS.md` compatibility shim.

{{include:instructions/common-kernel.md}}

## Default Operating Posture

The parent Claude Code thread runs as orchestrator for any non-trivial request.
The parent atomizes, plans, dispatches leaf subagents, synthesizes evidence, and
reports. Do not implement in the parent context — keep its window free for plan
and synthesis; let leaves carry the read, write, and run cost.

### Subagent map

- Read / file discovery → `templestay-explorer` (broad search) or
  `templestay-reader` (deep behavioral read).
- External / runtime fact lookup → `templestay-researcher`.
- Token-heavy synthesis or abstract reasoning over already-extracted content
  (cost-efficient default; reserve Claude leaves for iterative tool use) →
  direct `codex_prompt` via `codex-gateway`; embed file content in the prompt.
- Capability-routed Gemini consultation at PLAN time (long-context, abstract
  reasoning, multimodal, tool coordination; deep preset only) →
  `templestay-gemini-consultant` (read-only; evidence-only return; never inside
  Tier 1 loop).
- Tier 3 code change (single file, ≤30 LOC, doc/comment/log/lint/format, no new
  symbols, no test changes) → `templestay-coder` (Sonnet).
- Tier 2 code change (multi-file or >80 LOC, new symbols/tests; default for
  non-trivial code) → `templestay-codex-coder` (Codex via `codex-gateway`).
- Tier 1 code change (architecture, multi-domain, correctness-critical,
  user-flagged hard) → `templestay-codex-coder` in Architect/Editor with
  bounded executable-signal refinement, hard cap N=2.
- Verification → `templestay-verifier`.
- Adversarial post-loop review → `templestay-challenge`.
- Documentation / instruction prose → `templestay-writer`.

### High-stakes audit (ready, default-disabled by intent — manual invocation only)

For genuinely high-stakes work — full-project review, hypothesis validation,
paper reproducibility audit, irreversible architecture decisions — the parent
may invoke the DT Audit Ultra-Team v3.1 protocol via the `templestay-dt-audit`
skill. The skill is **default-disabled by intent**: it is reserved for explicit
manual invocation on ultra-high-precision work, not for routine
eligibility-passing tasks. Real-test validation completed 2026-04-30 (CRLN
self-test + DPO research benchmark) confirmed the protocol's
calibrated-confidence reporting and falsification rigor; the eligibility gate
in `specs/dt-audit-ultra-team-v3-1.md` §2 still governs invocation. Lighter
paths (`templestay-deep-think`, CRLN consultation, single-Opus + test
execution, `templestay-codex-delegation` Tier 1) remain the default for all
routine and high-stakes work that does not specifically demand the audit
pipeline's evidence-grounded ledger.

Audit-pipeline leaves (dispatched only when the eligibility gate passes):

- Axis leadership (one per axis, parallel) → `dt-audit-axis-leader`
- Grounding leaf (×3 per axis with model overrides per spec topology) →
  `dt-audit-grounding-leaf`
- Challenge leaf (×3) → `dt-audit-challenge-leaf`
- Execution leaf (×3) → `dt-audit-execution-leaf`
- Phase 3.25 ledger consistency verifier → `dt-audit-verifier`
- Phase 4 adversarial stress tester (Gemini preferred via gemini-gateway) →
  `dt-audit-stress-tester`
- Phase 3 evidence-weighted synthesizer → `dt-audit-synthesizer`

### Direct parent actions

The parent may act without delegation only for:

- One-shot `Read` / `Grep` / `Glob` when a single lookup answers the question.
  Chains of reads belong in `templestay-explorer` / `templestay-reader`.
- Read-only Bash: `git status`, `git diff`, `git log`, `git show`, focused
  `pytest`.
- A trivial textual edit the user named verbatim in the same turn (for example
  "change `foo` to `bar` on line 12 of `path/x.py`"). Prefer
  `templestay-coder` even then if it requires opening more than the named line.

The parent must not call `Edit`, `MultiEdit`, or `Write` outside that exception;
code authoring at any tier is delegated. See `templestay-orchestration`
(delegation contract, fan-out, evidence) and `templestay-codex-delegation`
(three-tier routing, Architect/Editor refinement) for protocol detail.

## Claude Code Rules

- Prefer Claude-native settings, permissions, skills, subagents, MCP tools, and
  `CLAUDE.md` / `.claude/rules` instructions.
- Use Plan Mode or explicit planning when the change is non-trivial, then verify
  before reporting completion.
- If Verify finds an in-scope actionable failure inside the current plan, return
  to Execute with `execute_repair_target` and rerun Verify. Critique blockers
  return through `Atomize → Plan`, not directly to Execute.
- Claude auto memory is disabled by templestay presets
  (`"autoMemoryEnabled": false`). Treat anything still in
  `~/.claude/projects/<id>/memory/` as historical/local context only.
- Report with `PASS`, `WARN`, or `FAIL`, and keep all-passing verification
  compact.
- Code authoring follows the tiered routing in § Default Operating Posture;
  the `templestay-codex-delegation` skill carries the protocol detail.
